Vascular Mechanisms for Sex Differences in MSIMI
To assess potential vascular mechanisms of sex differences in MSIMI, we examined whether resting hemodynamic and vascular measures, and their changes with mental stress, explained sex differences in MSIMI. These analyses were adjusted for body surface area and CAD severity (Gensini CAD severity score and single-photon emission computed tomography summed rest score). After including resting RPP and resting RHI to the mod-

el, the odds ratio of MSIMI for women compared with men was 2.6 (95% confidence interval, 1.3–5.4). Adding resting FMD to the model did not change the results (odds ratio, 2.6; 95% confidence interval, 1.3–5.3). Adjustment for change in RPP with mental stress (odds ratio, 2.7; 95% confidence interval, 1.3–5.4) and further adjustment for PAT ratio with mental stress (odds ratio, 3.0; 95% confidence interval, 1.5–6.4) also did not weaken the association between sex and MSIMI.
